  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law in the United States, money laundering is a serious offense with significant penalties. The penalties for money laundering depend on the specific statutes violated, but generally include the following:\n\n1. **Imprisonment**: Individuals convicted of money laundering can face up to **20 years** in federal prison for each count of money laundering under **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956** (which deals with the intent to promote illegal activity, conceal assets, or evade taxes). Under **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957** (which involves engaging in monetary transactions with criminally derived property), the maximum penalty is **10 years** per count.\n\n2. **Fines**: The fines for money laundering can be substantial. Under \u00a7 1956, the maximum fine is **$500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction, whichever is greater**. Under \u00a7 1957, the maximum fine is **$250,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction, whichever is greater**. Corporations or other entities may face fines of up to **$1 million or twice the value of the property**.\n\n3. **Forfeiture**: Individuals convicted of money laundering may also be subject to **asset forfeiture**, meaning the government can seize any property or funds involved in or derived from the illegal activity.\n\n4. **Additional Penalties**: Convictions for money laundering may also result in **restitution** to victims, **probation**, and a permanent **criminal record**, which can have long-term consequences for employment, professional licenses, and civil rights.\n\n5. **Enhanced Penalties for Aggravating Factors**: Penalties can be increased if the money laundering involves:  \n   - Transactions exceeding **$100,000**.  \n   - Violations occurring as part of a **pattern of illegal activity**.  \n   - Involvement in **drug trafficking** or **terrorism financing** (which can lead to stricter penalties under related statutes).\n\n6. **RICO Violations**: If money laundering is part of a broader racketeering enterprise under the **Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act (RICO)**, individuals could face **up to 20 years in prison** (or life if the underlying crime is punishable by life), fines, and forfeiture of assets.\n\nThe exact penalties depend on the specific circumstances of the case, including the amount of money involved, the nature of the underlying crime, and the individual\u2019s role in the scheme. If you or someone you know is facing money laundering charges, it is critical to consult with an experienced criminal defense attorney.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
